e to bioterrorism. Regulatory strategies in government and the courts are continually evolving and are affected by changing public perceptions of scientific knowledge. The legal and cultural shifts outlined in Becoming Biosubjects call into question what it means to be a Canadian, a citizen, and a human being.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBiotechnologyxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aBiotechnologyzCanadavPatents. 0aBioterrorismxPrevention. 0aBioterrorismzCanadaxPrevention. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzCanada. 0aForensic geneticsxTechnique. 0aGenetic engineeringxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aHuman body. 0aReproductive technologyxGovernment policyzCanada. 7aLAW / Science & Technology.2bisacsh1 aHamilton, Sheryl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSullivan, Rebecca, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266009040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442660090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442660090.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK